<subSubSection box="[199,1023,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,151,1653]" box="[199,1023,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</emphasis>
Species named in reference of its striking bicoloured pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1268,1293]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[343,581,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[343,581,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Holopothrips bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the species in the genus with a striking bicoloured body (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1428,1268,1293]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) and bears almost equiangular reticulation in the metanotum, without any internal markings (
<figureCitation box="[1236,1324,1303,1328]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), like the brown-coloured species 
<taxonomicName authority="Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski" authorityName="Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski" box="[424,846,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claritibialis">
<emphasis box="[424,590,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. claritibialis</emphasis>
Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hood" authorityName="Hood" box="[857,1086,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hambletoni">
<emphasis box="[857,1017,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. hambletoni</emphasis>
Hood
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Moulton. It" authorityName="Moulton. It" box="[1140,1410,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennatus">
<emphasis box="[1140,1275,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. pennatus</emphasis>
Moulton. It
</taxonomicName>
is also among the few species with multiple minute tubercles on the dorsolateral sculpture of head. This species shares with 
<taxonomicName box="[289,392,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvus">
<emphasis box="[289,392,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. fulvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having postocular setae minute and head with large eyes and curved cheeks, but is readily distinghished by its fully brown head (
<figureCitation box="[586,670,1447,1472]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), brown abdominal segment VIII and male pore plates occurring on abdominal sternites VI–VIII (
<figureCitation box="[481,564,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[584,821,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[584,821,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Holopothrips bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be related to the other seven bicoloured species of the genus whose body is mostly yellow, being distinguished by having the head and abdominal segment VIII fully brown, postocular setae about as long as the diameter of an ocellus and female spermatheca enlarged. A male and a female were studied from leaves of 
<emphasis box="[569,779,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Myrcia guianensis</emphasis>
collected in the city of Camaçari, 
<collectingRegion box="[1184,1252,1591,1616]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Bahia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1266,1337,1591,1616]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and are believed to belong to the same species.
</paragraph>
